#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:5
msgid "Portability Guidelines"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:7
msgid ""
"Emscripten can be used to compile almost any *portable* C++/C code to "
"JavaScript."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:9
msgid ""
"This section explains what types of code are non-portable (or more difficult "
"to port), and what code can be compiled but will run slowly. Developers can "
"use this information for evaluating the effort to port and re-write code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:12
msgid "Current Web limitations"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:14
msgid ""
"Multithreading depends on SharedArrayBuffer, which is still being "
"standardized and implemented by browsers. Emscripten has working support for "
"threads, which you can try in development browsers by setting the proper "
"preference."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:15
msgid "SIMD is also in the process of standardization and implementation."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:18
msgid "Code that cannot be compiled"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:20
msgid ""
"The following types of code would need to be re-written in order to work "
"with Emscripten. (While in theory it might be possible for Emscripten to "
"work around these issues using emulation, it would be very slow.)"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:22
msgid ""
"Code relying on a big-endian architecture. Emscripten-compiled code "
"currently requires a little-endian host to run on, which accounts for 99% of "
"machines connected to the internet. This is because JavaScript typed arrays "
"(used for views on memory) obey the host byte ordering and LLVM needs to "
"know which endianness to target."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:23
msgid ""
"Code that uses low-level features of the native environment, for example "
"native stack manipulation in conjunction with ``setjmp``/``longjmp`` (we "
"support proper ``setjmp``/``longjmp``, i.e., jumping down the stack, but not "
"jumping up to an unwound stack, which is undefined behavior)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:24
msgid ""
"Code that scans registers or the stack. This won't work because a variable "
"in a register or on the stack may be held in a JavaScript local variable "
"(which cannot be scanned)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:26
msgid ""
"Code of this type might be used for conservative garbage collection. You can "
"do conservative scanning when there is no other code on the stack, e.g. from "
"an iteration of the main event loop. Other solutions include the "
"SpillPointers pass in Binaryen."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:28
msgid ""
"Code with architecture-specific inline assembly (like an ``asm()`` "
"containing x86 code) is not portable. That code would need to be replaced "
"with portable C or C++. Sometimes a codebase will have both portable code "
"and optional inline assembly as an optimization, so you might find an option "
"to disable the inline assembly."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:32
msgid "Code that compiles but might run slowly"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:34
msgid "Understanding these issues can be helpful when optimising code."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:36
msgid ""
"The following types of code will compile, but may not run as fast as "
"expected:"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:38
msgid ""
"In asm.js (but not WebAssembly), 64-bit ``int`` variables. Mathematical "
"operations (+, -, \\*, /) are slow because they are emulated (bitwise "
"operations are reasonably fast). JavaScript does not have a native 64-bit "
"``int`` type so this is unavoidable."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:39
msgid ""
"C++ Exceptions. In JavaScript such code generally makes the JavaScript "
"engine turn off various optimizations. For that reason exceptions are turned "
"off by default in ``-O1`` and above. To re-enable them, run *emcc* with ``-"
"sDISABLE_EXCEPTION_CATCHING=0`` (see `src/settings.js <https://github.com/"
"emscripten-core/emscripten/blob/1.29.12/src/settings.js#L298>`_)."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:40
msgid ""
"``setjmp`` also prevents :term:`relooping` around it, forcing us to emulate "
"control flow using a less efficient approach."
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:44
msgid "Other issues"
msgstr ""

#: ../../../source/docs/porting/guidelines/portability_guidelines.rst:46
msgid ""
"Code that relies on x86 alignment behavior. x86 allows unaligned reads and "
"writes (so for example you can read a 16-bit value from a non-even address), "
"but other architectures do not (32-bit ARM will raise ``SIGILL``). For asm."
"js loads and stores are forced to aligned offsets; for WebAssembly unaligned "
"loads and stores will work but may be slow depending on the underlying CPU. "
"If you build your code with ``SAFE_HEAP=1`` then you will get a clear "
"runtime exception, see :ref:`Debugging`."
msgstr ""
